{
  "id": "study-chicago-house-001",
  "version": "1.0",
  "title": "Chicago House \u2014 Four Four Foundation",
  "subtitle": "The swing that made 1991 feel inevitable",
  "annotation": "The foundational four-on-the-floor of early Chicago house. Kick lands on every beat \u2014 no variation, no apology. Snare and clap lock to beats 2 and 4 at medium velocity; the clap is not an accent, it is a commitment. Hats run straight 8th notes with swing pulling the off-beats just behind. The open hat sits on the 'and' of beat 4, not beat 3 \u2014 that placement is structural, not ornamental. What not to correct: the laziness of the hat feel is the point. Tightening it toward the grid removes the pocket. The pattern loops every two bars to give the kick space to breathe.",
  "grooveProfile": {
    "swingFeel": "Lazy 8th-note triplet push. Off-beats sit behind the grid by 25-35 ticks. The feel is unhurried.",
    "accentLogic": "Kick carries the weight. Snare and clap are structural, not expressive. No accent on the hat.",
    "microtimingTendencies": "Straight two-bar loop. No cross-bar feel. Groove repeats identically every bar."
  },
